headline: Critics blast ABC pundit for 'sexist' tweet aimed at Republican Rep. Elise Stefanik
subHeadline: ABC News chief political analyst Matthew Dowd deletes and apologizes for offending tweet; reaction on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello everybody. I'm Jesse Watters along with Katie Pavlich, Juan Williams, Dana Perino, and Greg Gutfeld. It's five o'clock in New York City. And this is “The Five.” Democrats could be setting themselves up for a serious case of impeachment buyer's remorse. Remember, they promised us a bombshell testimony from their star witnesses yesterday, but Adam Schiff's spectacle failed to deliver. That dud could now prove to be a very costly mistake for Nancy Pelosi and her Democratic pals.  Of course, the liberal media is coming to the rescue. Check them out trying to reset the narrative by spinning what happened at the hearing.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: That phone call. This was a bombshell.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: The big bombshell today.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: What did you make of the bombshell?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Going back to the bombshell, devastating testimony.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Devastating.

utterances.speaker: WOLF BLITZER, CNN HOST
utterances.sentences: Devastating new information.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Bribery.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Attempted bribery.

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO, CNN HOST
utterances.sentences: It was an attempted bribe.

utterances.speaker: JOHN DEAN, CNN CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.sentences: They already have more that t they had against Richard Nixon to impeach him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And if you are wondering what the Democrats impeachment is really about, AOC just set it out loud. Listen.

utterances.speaker: REP. ALEXANDRIA OCASIO-CORTEZ, D-N.Y.
utterances.sentences: At the end of the day, we have to be able to come together as the caucus. And if it is this Ukrainian allegation that what brings the caucus together, then I think we have to run with however we unify the House.  We also need to move quite quickly because we are talking about the potential compromise of the 2020 elections. And so, this is not just about something that has occurred. This is about preventing a potentially disastrous outcome from occurring next year.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She said it out loud, Dana. You're not supposed to say that.

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, the thing is, I don't think the problem in the caucus is that they don't have an agreement on impeachment. They do have agreement on impeachment. The problem the Democrats have is that they don't agree on which way the country should go. Continue with free market capitalism or socialism. They have the divide is not about not liking Donald Trump. They got a 99 percent agreement on not liking Donald Trump, so I don't think that the consensus that they needed was not necessarily about this, except I do think that Nancy Pelosi is probably going to have to look at them and say, I told you that this was not a good idea. You wanted us to do it.  And you know, I read a ton of news this morning, a run from the farthest left to the all the way into the middle to the middle to the farthest right. And my consensus this morning was that nobody woke up this morning thinking that impeachment is an imperative.   That day one did not change anybody's minds. And that they have this buyer's remorse thinking, OK. Now if the president were to lose next November, it won't be because of impeachment. It will because of lots of other facts and turn out and all of that. Now if he wins, and he --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- improves his total in the Electoral College or in the popular vote I do think that the Republicans and probably a lot of the Democrats will look back and say impeachment help him get there.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You know, I think he raised $3.1 million just yesterday on the first day of impeachment, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.sentences: The Democrats there up ship creek without a paddle.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Thank you. The media, I like the media, because they are complaining about not being take -- how this is not being taken seriously by the public. Like they expect more people to be enraged. They are acting like the film director after the movie bombs that first weekend and they read rotten tomatoes and it's just saying your movie sucks. And it is their movie. The media helped direct this film. So, they are taking this rejection personally which is why you see CNN complaining about all the right-wingers who are telling viewers not to take this seriously.  But it wasn't a hearing. It was a say on. The entire process was based on the power to read minds. It's like they needed they thought they could see into Trump's brain, but you can't see his thoughts. You can see his actions, right?  So that's why everybody was like going, there's nothing here. The worst part about this whole thing, and it's kind of funny but sad, they sent therapy dogs to --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That was a coincidence.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Was that a coincidence?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Thank God.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's a good story, though.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Well, tell me the story.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: There was --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There they are.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: This group was planning for months ahead of time. They were scheduled to be there on the Hill. They just happened to be there on the day of the impeachment. So, then some people thought that they were brought in for impeachment. It was just a coincidence.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What I love about it because I'm going to pretend you never said that. Is that, these clowns manufactured the anxiety that they now pretend to suffer from. We are going to edit all of that out imposed.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: We're not live right now?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No. This is a free taste.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK. This is on tape.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Simulation --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: To Greg's point about the audience now being blamed by the press for I guess not understanding the bombshell, they're not understanding the complexities of these high crimes and misdemeanors. Juan, the Kavanaugh hearing, the Comey hearing, and even the Michael Cohen hearing had bigger ratings than this first impeachment hearing. What does that tell you?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, HOST
utterances.sentences: What does that tell me?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I mean, first of all, Nancy Pelosi said I don't know why anyone would think that Nancy Pelosi has regrets. She said today she thought the witnesses corroborated a bribery case against the president of the United States. That's pretty significant to me.  But I noticed that when I'm listening to conservative Trump media, they say hey, you know what, Stephanie Graham, White House press secretary, this was a joke. Donald Trump, Jr., this is insanity. Some of the talk show host, don't watch it. A waste of time. This is stupid.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That same it's me who said that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Did you say that? OK, Greg said that too.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Greg said yesterday.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right, all right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: On the Fox had the number one, we had the most viewers.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. Thank you. That's because --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The show did very well. Thank you, Adam Schiff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, to my mind, it's like you know what, you get separate audiences in separate silos, right? And the message to the conservatives, don't worry. Don't pay attention. Don't listen, because it might change your mind and we don't want anybody to change their mind.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, Juan, Fox News was the largest audience.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I agree.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So how is --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But the message because the message --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- how is the people -- how are people not paying attention?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- not only here, but I'm talking about on a lot of the conservative talk shows and the like was this is to be ignored even though this is a historic event --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Not historic.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: It is historic.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: This is a remedy that the founding fathers put in place for when the executive, when the president is abusing his power. They're not -- right now --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's not even the case.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: -- remember, they're not building a final case. This is like, you know, this is not a criminal proceeding.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But the analogy would be like a grand jury, they are looking for a preponderance of evidence and testimony.

utterances.speaker: KATIE PAVLICH, HOST
utterances.sentences: But they didn't get it today.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And you know what, public sentiment has shifted on impeachment, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I know it has, Juan. I think it might be shifting away from --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And it's more in favor. Well, yes, but we know it's really high.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: If you look at the Republicans on the committee, they are not the one saying that you shouldn't be watching. In fact, they are saying we want to present even more people and different kinds of evidence to the American people. And Adam Schiff is refusing to do so. The question I think for Schiff going forward is going to be what is his strategy? Is he going to continue down this road inevitably of wanting to bring articles of impeachment on the floor for a vote? Because at this point, you kind of has to. He's made all these claims about how serious this is, how it's a threat to the country.  Of course, that's what they would have to do to maintain his own credibility and his own ego, because he is leading the charge on this. Or, are they going to now shift the goal post and make different accusations? So, with Russia was there's all this collusion. And then when they couldn't prove collusion they move to obstruction. Are they now going to move the argument down the down as they continue not to get the corroboration that they need to make the case?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And Dana, if this does go to the Senate, does that mean if there's a Senate trial that every senator must be there throughout the entire deal? Because a lot of the senators are going to be running for president.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, it's pretty interesting, actually. So pretty much, if you are a senator, you can choose not to go, but then you just increase the chances that the Republicans are able to acquit because of the votes. But yes, think of Kamala Harris, Senator Booker --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Booker, Warren.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- Bernie Sanders.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Bernie.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I can't remember there's others senators running. Apologies if I'm not remembering you.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Klobuchar.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Thank you. Klobuchar from Minnesota. So, yes. So, it's about a six-hour ordeal every day six days a week, and you can imagine that Mitch McConnell would be like, I'll just sit here for two months. In January, in February. And you think that Iowa is in February, the first week of February, New Hampshire the second week. Super Tuesday right after that. And also, if you are a juror as a senator, you are not allowed to talk about it. So, because --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Do you think they can keep this to themselves?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, that's why I think that every -- I think that this is going to come to a pretty quick conclusion.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: In the House.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: In the Senate.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: In the Senate.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes, like a rush like, yes, let's get this over. But let me just say, Dana, to you --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan, you can do an impeachment by a whole --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But how is it beneficial to Democrats?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No. I think they -- look, to Dana's point about, if Mitch McConnell scratches this out to embarrass the Democrats and prevent them from campaigning, don't forget Democrats think this is good.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: We'll have to see.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's the purest example of an orchestrated event meant to manipulate the public, right? Because now we're watching it and what did we see? Witnesses who didn't witness anything. We knew from the start this was a sham.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right. I told you so. Impeachment hearings star Republican Congresswoman Elise Stefanik, hit with a very sexist smear by the liberal mainstream media. Details on that ahead.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Congresswoman Elise Stefanik coming under attack after mixing it up at the impeachment hearing. Watch.

utterances.speaker: REP. ELISE STEFANIK, R-N.Y.
utterances.sentences: Will you be prohibiting witnesses from answering member's questions as you have in the closed-door deposition? Only one member in their staff --

utterances.speaker: REP. ADAM SCHIFF, D-CALIF.
utterances.sentences: The gentlewoman --

utterances.speaker: STEFANIK
utterances.sentences: -- on this committee has direct knowledge of the identity of the whistleblower.

utterances.speaker: SCHIFF
utterances.sentences: The gentlewoman will suspend.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: ABC News chief political analyst Matthew Dowd going after Stefanik in a tweet, many are calling sexist. He wrote, quote, "Elise Stefanik is a perfect example of why just electing someone because they are a woman or a millennial doesn't necessarily get you the leaders we need." Dowd later deleted that tweet and apologized. Stefanik accepted it, but also added that ABC, quote, "You should be ashamed of your comment. This is one of the reasons young women don't run for office." Katie, let me go to you. You followed this issue; you know both of them.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What do you think?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: He made it worse, because he deleted the tweet, she already issued an apology and then said we not only need to elect people not just because they are women or because they are millennials, but because they need integrity. So then, he implied that she had no integrity and that's why she was in office without any of that. It's a gross tweet. You try to walk it back and then he was patronizing and saying, you know, I made a bad statement --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And they know each other actually.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: -- but I've done a lot for women. Right, and she worked for him in college to help write a book and this is the way that he has repaid her. So, if he didn't think that she was competent then --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Another example of Twitter not making anything better.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The other thing that happened with her, Greg, last week is she is the youngest congresswoman I think, I guess maybe Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez could be different. I can't remember --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: She was first and then she --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: She was the first.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Republican.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The youngest first Republican, anyway, she had a lot of firsts. But she didn't get on the cover of Glamour magazine and all the other things.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Of course.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So, apparently last week during the hearing or in the closed-door hearing.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: She goes to ask a question to a witness and the witness' lawyer said I'm sorry, I didn't think staff was allowed to ask questions. And she very graciously said, it's OK. It happens all the time. She is a young woman.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She is young woman. I can see that, Dana. How condescending.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What would like to say about her?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think what Dowd said was absolutely right. You shouldn't elect somebody because of what they are. It's who they are. Or is it the reverse. Now you know what I mean.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: What they think, but you should agree, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But you don't elect somebody because they are black. You don't elect somebody because they are white. You don't elect somebody because they are woman. You don't elect somebody because they are a man. You elect somebody because they are persuasive, they've got talent. Having said that though, I've changed my mind four times on the story. You could bet if she were on the other side, right? If she was going after, they would -- they would say she is a national contender for the presidency.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: So, we know that's what Dowd would say. But she's on the other side so he smears her. But then, he apologized. And you are supposed to accept every apology. I believe you should.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes, I agree.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You should accept every apology.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And she did.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. But then he did that day --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Then he made it worse.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The he did, then he made it worse.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Again.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And it's like, OK, then not a real apology, and it goes back to, but then again, but it's only a tweet. So, I go back to your point earlier. Twitter makes everything and everybody worse. You are never a better version of yourself on Twitter. I know that personally. I am much worse on Twitter than I am here. If you can imagine how I am here, it's really bad.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, do you think that you are worse on Twitter?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't do anything on Twitter.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, he don't --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I play it safe. Let's put it that way.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: So, that, ironically, that makes you a better person on Twitter?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's sexism.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: It's a danger zone for Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You know, I think I have a very good ear for sexism.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Because a lot a lot of sexism is directed at me.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's directed at you?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes. My hair. You know, I pretend like it doesn't bother me, but it does. It does. I don't know. Does he have a crush on her?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: No, no, no, no.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Explain this away because I disagree with you, Greg. I think this is blunt sexism.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I think she's actually a very confident, Harvard educated, aggressive defender of impeachment. She's on the intelligence committee.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Against impeachment.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Defender of -- yes, against impeachment.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And she is very popular in her district.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She's very popular. She wasn't elected because she was a woman or because she was young. She is obviously very talented. And she didn't do anything in that hearing that Dowd was watching to invite any sort of ridicule.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: true.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And if you remember, Juan, when she was first running, she was running against --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It convinced me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- she was I think primary against two older Republican males who also did kind of the same thing.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Like what would you go at the show. But she really worked and made her way. But she apparently rubbed Adam Schiff the wrong way when she was basically saying, aren't you going to allow us to have any of these witnesses and he thought it was inappropriate.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I think a lot of people thought it was a concerted effort that started even before Congresswoman Stefanik spoke to try to disrupt the hearing and get Schiff off his game. But you know, the idea, a woman and a millennial. To me, it could be good, it could be bad. And that's why the tweet was wrong. I mean, to me, the tweet is offensive. I'm sure I disagree with Ms. Stefanik on lots of things, but not on this one. I think that you know, you got to remember too that Matt Dowd is a Republican. So, I mean, this is not --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Independent.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: He change his party.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: His history is as a Republican. He was -- he was a presidential advisor. So, to me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: We don't want him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: To me, this is, but to get back to this point about Twitter. You know. So, the other day, there was a situation where somebody said, OK boomer. And then an AARP official came back and said, yes, but us, we boomers, we have all the money. And then that set off a huge brawl --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Roasted.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes, exactly. And I thought to myself, this gets us nowhere. It's like, is this entertainment for some people? But she should, anyway, you shouldn't have insulted the congresswoman.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Also, to make another point, ABC, I mean, that's his boss. He should stop criticizing this congresswoman. They've been criticized, ABC, because they've been covering up a lot of nasty stuff over there.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: And Adam Schiff especially doesn't like Elise Stefanik because she was the first person to point that there may have been some communication between the chairman and the whistleblower.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: She noted the date of the letter, and the complaint, and has been calling him out.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Super smart.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Since they got the complaint about why he held it from the rest of the committee and wants more transparency about who they can and cannot talk to.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Now I've changed my mind again, Dana. He, Dowd should be fired. He should be fired.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You're so open-minded, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No. Well, it's five times now I've changed my mind today.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, we'll give it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You should run for office.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- we'll go to commercial break and see how you feel after that. Coming up, campaign trail chaos as yet another Democrat jumps in. Plus, Hillary Clinton claims she is being pressured to run.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Sweet. The 2020 Democratic field being shaken up yet again. Former Massachusetts Governor, Deval Patrick, now officially in the race today. Meanwhile, Hillary Clinton is claiming she's being pressured to run in 2020.

utterances.speaker: HILLARY CLINTON, FORMER UNITED STATES SECRETARY OF STATE
utterances.sentences: I, as I say, never, never, never say never. And I will certainly tell you, I'm under enormous pressure from many, many, many people to think about it, but as of this moment, sitting here in this studio talking to you, that is absolutely not in my plans.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, Katie, I don't think she is running, but you never know. I don't know what that was about, but I do -- I'm interested in asking what do you make of Deval Patrick?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.sentences: Well, first, I want to say Hillary Clinton's, everyone is asking you to run, I think it reminds me when Joe Biden said that he told Obama not to endorse him. Everyone is like, yes, Joe. Sure. But Deval Patrick, look, you know, there's always more room in the stage at this point. His time to file. He's an interesting candidate. His background is different than other people on the stage. He's a capitalist. He is a minority. utterances.utterance: She's very popular. She wasn't elected because she was a woman or because she was young. She is obviously very talented. And she didn't do anything in that hearing that Dowd was watching to invite any sort of ridicule.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: true.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And if you remember, Juan, when she was first running, she was running against --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It convinced me.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- she was I think primary against two older Republican males who also did kind of the same thing.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like what would you go at the show. But she really worked and made her way. But she apparently rubbed Adam Schiff the wrong way when she was basically saying, aren't you going to allow us to have any of these witnesses and he thought it was inappropriate.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think a lot of people thought it was a concerted effort that started even before Congresswoman Stefanik spoke to try to disrupt the hearing and get Schiff off his game. I'm sure I disagree with Ms. Stefanik on lots of things, but not on this one. I think that you know, you got to remember too that Matt Dowd is a Republican. So, I mean, this is not --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Independent.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, no.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He change his party.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: His history is as a Republican. He was -- he was a presidential advisor. So, to me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: We don't want him.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: To me, this is, but to get back to this point about Twitter. You know. So, the other day, there was a situation where somebody said, OK boomer. And then an AARP official came back and said, yes, but us, we boomers, we have all the money. And then that set off a huge brawl --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Roasted.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, exactly. And I thought to myself, this gets us nowhere. It's like, is this entertainment for some people? But she should, anyway, you shouldn't have insulted the congresswoman.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Also, to make another point, ABC, I mean, that's his boss. He should stop criticizing this congresswoman. They've been criticized, ABC, because they've been covering up a lot of nasty stuff over there.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: And Adam Schiff especially doesn't like Elise Stefanik because she was the first person to point that there may have been some communication between the chairman and the whistleblower.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: She noted the date of the letter, and the complaint, and has been calling him out.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Super smart.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Since they got the complaint about why he held it from the rest of the committee and wants more transparency about who they can and cannot talk to.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Now I've changed my mind again, Dana. He, Dowd should be fired. He should be fired.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You're so open-minded, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No. Well, it's five times now I've changed my mind today.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, we'll give it --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You should run for office.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- we'll go to commercial break and see how you feel after that. Coming up, campaign trail chaos as yet another Democrat jumps in. Plus, Hillary Clinton claims she is being pressured to run.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Sweet. The 2020 Democratic field being shaken up yet again. Former Massachusetts Governor, Deval Patrick, now officially in the race today. Meanwhile, Hillary Clinton is claiming she's being pressured to run in 2020.

utterances.speaker: HILLARY CLINTON, FORMER UNITED STATES SECRETARY OF STATE
utterances.utterance: I, as I say, never, never, never say never. And I will certainly tell you, I'm under enormous pressure from many, many, many people to think about it, but as of this moment, sitting here in this studio talking to you, that is absolutely not in my plans.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, Katie, I don't think she is running, but you never know. I don't know what that was about, but I do -- I'm interested in asking what do you make of Deval Patrick?

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Well, first, I want to say Hillary Clinton's, everyone is asking you to run, I think it reminds me when Joe Biden said that he told Obama not to endorse him. Everyone is like, yes, Joe. Sure. But Deval Patrick, look, you know, there's always more room in the stage at this point. His time to file. He's an interesting candidate. His background is different than other people on the stage. He's a capitalist. He is a minority. He allegedly and reportedly has the blessing of Barack Obama, which will help him only I think behind the scenes with some fund-raising numbers, but also going into the primary process and if he wins the general -- or the primary. So, look, I read the comments on the Twitter announcement that he made through the video and they were not good. People were really mad about it's too late. Everyone else has done all of the work. There is not enough room for you. Get out. You are an evil hedge fund guy, financial guy. But I think, you know, he has good proximity with New Hampshire. He has a lot of work to make up in terms of going to Iowa, as Andrew Yang was saying, knocking on doors, getting people to vote for him. But maybe he's not banking on Iowa just like Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana, you know what strikes me is, Michael Bloomberg, who's also it looks like he's going to get into the race now. So, you have Bloomberg and Deval Patrick it seems to me both taking aim at Joe Biden, with the assumption being that if Biden collapses, they would win Biden voters, kind of sent Democrats. But Biden is not collapsing.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, and I think that you'll see some more of that coming out in the polls next week or so. Elizabeth -- I actually think that he's going after Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders, that Bloomberg is. Maybe they think Biden won't be able to go the distance or that he's already been so damage by these allegations about bribery and Burisma and Hunter Biden. That they think he won't be able to do it. Plus, he can't raise that much money. Bloomberg, I think, is a much harder sell than somebody like Deval Patrick.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think that he has a much greater chance of being able to deliver an Obama-esque-type message. I think he would give Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren a run for their money in New Hampshire. Might not be able to beat Buttigieg in Iowa who is doing very well. But I think that this race actually for all the -- I really believe it would be narrowed down by now, but it's actually growing. And I think there's probably room for it to grow.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Huh. She wants more people on the stage, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, it's a weak field. It's wide open. There could be a catastrophe next summer and here's how. If you right now see Joe Biden collapse and not win Iowa and New Hampshire, right? And then, you have Bernie and Warren split the socialism vote and all the donors don't really open the wallet, Pete doesn't have enough juice to run up through the middle, you could have after super Tuesday and then no one else getting in going into the convention. No one hits that delegate ceiling. And you could have a huge bloodbath at the convention.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Think of the past.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And we are going to have the best time covering it here on the Five.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Maybe the Democrat will nominate Trump. Hey, but, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Just to pick up on this point, you know, I like Deval Patrick. I personally know Deval Patrick, but what do they say, you are no Obama. I mean, Obama's charisma.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. There will never be another Obama.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. Because when I hear people say that he could like, you know what, I think of Obama at what year was the convention in Boston --

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: O-four.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: O-four. That John Kerry -- that's a famous speech. I don't know if Deval Patrick can deliver that speech.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But didn't some of the lines from Obama's speeches come from Deval Patrick?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He wasn't --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Don't you remember all that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes, it's delivered. All right. So, Greg, I was just coming to you on this. You know, to me, if you don't know what Deval Patrick is doing --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: -- it looks like well, he's a great guy. People like him. He was a governor. But he's just tilting at wind mills. Why now?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think he's actually probably one of the strongest people out there if he gets Obama's endorsement.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's going to be great. But all this people joining reflects the Democrat dysfunction, right? I call it electile dysfunction. Electile dysfunction because I wrote down that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You're on a roll today.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: This is a party without a plan, right? OK. It's like a bus on a road trip, no map, no GPS, but they got 20, 25 backseat drivers. They all left to D.C. to Seattle, but they're now in Anchorage, Alaska and they're trying to change a flat with a banana. I mean, they are in trouble. utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He's like, you don't take a bus. You fly.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You fly. And Deval is like -- Deval is a strong candidate. He should have entered -- he should have entered earlier.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: You know it's bad when Hillary is like, everyone is telling me.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: By the way --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I wonder if she names one person.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, we're saying that, there's -- that's what you say when you try to exist the conversation. It's like saying sorry for your loss at a funeral. They come up to her, they go, here she is, you should run again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, know what, we have time. Here's Hillary saying what it would have been like if she was president.

utterances.speaker: CLINTON
utterances.utterance: Look, I think all the time about what kind of President I would have been and what I would have done differently and what I think it would have meant to our country and the world. So, of course I think about it, I think about it all the time.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I'm tired of being her shrink, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I was just saying.

utterances.utterance: She is using America as her therapist.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

Did McCain think he would have been better than Obama, yes. You could go on - everybody who lost thinks they would have been a better President than the person who won. utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She just doesn't want to spend time with Bill.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.speaker: PERINO

utterances.speaker: PERINO

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think they were critical at times.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, very rarely. And they went on to do other things.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.utterance: PC police alert watching classic kids' movies like this could be offensive.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: That's right. New streaming service Disney Plus slapping a warning on classic animated flicks like Dumbo and Lady and The Tramp. It's cautioning fans that there could be a quote outdated cultural depiction that may be triggering. So, Greg, our local cultural expert.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I am. That's true.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: What are your thoughts on this?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, this is another example, what we're seeing constantly is an out of proportion response to the activism of today. Nobody wants to be the object of a mob on Twitter. You know kids these days, Dana, they don't have - kids today don't have the giddy thrill of sneaking into an R rated film and knowing that's a possibility you might see partial nudity. My sister Jeannie took me to see Animal House. Was it 1979, 1978? I wasn't - I was 14. I wasn't allowed to see that, and I saw stuff that I could not unseen. Thank you, Jeannie.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: So, Jesse.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No one does that anymore.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The good old days.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: No rules. So, Jesse, Lady and The Tramp is allegedly offensive because the song, we are Siamese is performed by two cats speaking in a stereotypical Asian accent. They have examples for all of the other films that we named. Should they be--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well. Yes.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Should they just not show these films at all if they're going to be--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: This is backlash by the Left by just putting a disclaimer and I think a disclaimer is fine. I'm OK with the disclaimer, don't butcher the whole movie. But I agree, there are obviously like from the 50s and the 60s and the 70s where they depict foreigners or other ethnic groups or racial groups in a demeaning or a dopey way.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And we understand that that's wrong and that's hurtful, OK. But you can also as a cartoon depict other groups in a humorous harmless way as well by just you know portraying certain characteristics of certain groups that are common understanding among all people. And you don't do it in a nasty way.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Are you talking about the Jews.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: But if you didn't create the film, you're growing up in the year 2019 and you're a 5-year-old kid, would you know that these things were stereotypical, or would you just be watching the film. utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Kids don't know this; they just accept it for what it is.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: OK, so is pointing it out to the kids necessary?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, yes. I mean look, two points to make here. That's not right. That was a caricature.

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Right. But that's my point. Unless you pointed out and say that this was, I don't know that kids would necessarily know that that's what it meant.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I watched Dumbo a lot.

utterances.utterance: What is it in Dumbo, by the way?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

I'm OK with the disclaimer. That's fine, but I don't like that this is also happening with school districts banning books. utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Learn from it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But like with you know - was it the Prime Minister of Canada or the Governor of Virginia, blackface was once accepted especially for young white men--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Apparently, it's still is.

utterances.utterance: Prime Minister.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I better stay out of your neighborhood.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: If he was a conservative, he would have lost his job.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The disclaimer.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.speaker: PAVLICH
utterances.utterance: Governor Northam, we don't know if he was in blackface or the KKK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right. What a choice. But the point is that young white guys thought, yes, there is nothing wrong with this.

utterances.utterance: No. You know what that calls for, a quick recline as far as you can, snap those legs right back.
